-- BHP Billiton, BSkyB, Vodafone, WPP: U.K., Irish Equity Preview
-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   A l e x i s   X y d i a s
-- 2010-12-30T07:40:30Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-29/bp-capital-shopping-centres-wpp-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  The benchmark  FTSE 100 Index  declined 12.56, or 0.2
percent, to 5,996.36. The gauge is headed for a 2010 advance of
11 percent. The  FTSE All-Share Index  fell less than 0.1 percent,
while Ireland’s  ISEQ Index  rose 0.4 percent.       BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BLT LN): The mining company may make a
$90-a-share bid for U.S. independent oil and natural gas
producer Anadarko Petroleum Inc., the Daily Mail reported,
without saying where it obtained the information. BHP shares
rose 0.2 percent to 2,616 pence.  Balfour Beatty Plc  (BBY LN): The company said Gammon
Construction, the infrastructure contractor in Hong Kong in
which Balfour has a 50 percent shareholding, has won a series of
infrastructure contracts worth a total of 190 million pounds
($295 million). The shares rose 1.6 percent to 317.8 pence.       British Sky Broadcasting Plc  (BSY LN): Ofcom, Britain’s
media regulator, will probably recommend tomorrow that Rupert
Murdoch’s bid to buy the remaining 61 percent of BSkyB, a pay-TV
company, should be subject to a further six-month inquiry, the
Guardian reported, without citing anyone. The shares lost 0.8
percent to 740.5 pence.       Colt Group SA  (COLT LN): The communications company said it
will appoint Mark Ferrari as chief financial officer, effective
March 31. The shares rose 0.9 percent to 134.7 pence.  Vodafone Group Plc  (VOD LN): The world’s largest mobile-
phone company is ready to start talks to sell its 7 billion-
pound stake in SFR to Vivendi SA, the Daily Mail reported,
citing people familiar with the matter. The shares lost 1.9
percent to 168.85 pence.  WPP Plc  (WPP LN): The world’s largest advertising company
is set to buy Blue State Digital, the agency that worked on the
“Obama for America” online campaign, Sky News reported,
without saying where it got the information. The shares were
unchanged at 794 pence.  To contact the reporters on this story:
